{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511287"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:40:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:40:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11734"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11734"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.03,0.44,0.37,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4347"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54018"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4347"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11734"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39490"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"3832"},{"type":"tags","id":"3833"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5971"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6650"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16059"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18507"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42654"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54018"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a painless, ulcerated lesion on his left middle finger (Image). This has been present for about eight months and is slowly increasing in size. On physical examination, the patient has numerous solar keratoses on a background of solar damaged skin. Examination is otherwise unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Imiquimod cream","Cryotherapy","Skin biopsy","Wide local excision","Excision and axillary node sampling"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows a raised skin lesion with central ulceration. The history describes the lesion as slow-growing, which could be in keeping with a developing skin malignancy, including basal cell carcinoma (BCC), squamous cell carcinoma (SCC), or melanoma (in this case given the clinical appearance amelanotic melanoma). Differential diagnoses include ulcerated rheumatoid nodules, gouty tophi, and atypical infection including deep fungal and atypical mycobacterium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is required to confirm the diagnosis histologically. A punch biopsy of the lesion at the ulcer edge or a shave excision of the lesion would be the appropriate biopsy options. If a skin malignancy is confirmed, definitive treatment of the lesion would involve complete excision of the lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhysical treatments of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecryotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E and topical immunomodulators such as \u003Cstrong\u003EImiquimod cream\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to treat superficial and in situ skin malignancies, as well as treat pre-malignant lesions e.g. actinic keratoses. The induration and ulceration of this lesion suggests it is a more advanced lesion, whereby these treatments are unlikely to be effective in completely treating the lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWide local excision\u003C/strong\u003E (WLE) would typically be performed following histopathological confirmation of the lesion. If there was a strong pre-test probability of skin malignancy (e.g. if the patient had a history of multiple non-melanoma skin cancers) it would be reasonable to consider WLE or an excisional biopsy at the outset, however this would depend on the patient and treating doctor\u0027s preferences.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcision and axillary node sampling\u003C/strong\u003E is also used for lesions with a high suspicion of malignancy. The metastasis rate of non-melanoma skin cancers is approximately 2%.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ulcerated lesions should raise suspicion for non-melanoma skin cancer."],"references":["Arasu A, Meah N, Sinclair R. Skin checks in primary care. Aust J Gen Pract. 2019;48(9):614-619. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/september/skin-checks-in-primary-care"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39490"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11734"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16253"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16253"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2413eb0c-f461-4530-937e-308c30dbdf0c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2413eb0c-f461-4530-937e-308c30dbdf0c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":408}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39490"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-28T23:20:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-05T13:19:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4347"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54018"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":nul